value.value: Any fatty acid that contains an unsaturated bond originating from the 3rd carbon from the methyl end. Omega-3 fatty acids do not occur naturally with chain lengths shorter than 16 carbon units.

A serrated polypoid lesion that arises in the colon.  It is usually found in the distant colon and it rarely produces symptoms.  This group includes goblet cell rich, mucin poor, and microvesicular hyperplastic polyps.

One of a variable number of incomplete, C-shaped cartilaginous rings encircling the anterolateral portion of the trachea, which are horizontally stacked and separated by narrow intervals throughout the length of the trachea.
Any of the glands located at the wall of the urethra of male mammals that produce and secrete mucus, a major component of semen.
The thin layer of cells that line the lumen of a vein carrying deoxygenated blood.
The layer of cells that line the lumen of the vena cava.
The layer of cells that line the lumen of a venule.

A circumscribed neoplasm that arises from the glandular epithelium of the duodenum. Morphologically, it is characterized by a proliferation of neoplastic glandular cells and it is associated with dysplasia. According to the growth pattern, it may be classified as tubular, villous, or tubulovillous.
The layer of cells that line the lumen of any vessels that is part of the venous system.
The non-striated muscle tissue surrounding the blood vessels that are part of the venous system.
The adrenal gland located on the left side of the body.
The testis on the left side of the body.
The ureter connecting the left kidney to the bladder.
The adrenal gland located on the right side of the body.
The testis on the right side of the body.
The ureter connecting the right kidney to the bladder.

The tissue that constitutes the retina. It is composed of the following layers: ganglion cell layer, inner limiting membrane, inner nuclear layer, inner plexiform layer, layer of the ophthalmic nerve fibers, layer of the rods and cones, neural retina, outer limiting membrane, outer nuclear layer, outer plexiform layer, and retinal pigment epithelium.
The layer of cells that lines the arterial system.
A benign or malignant neoplasm that affects the epiglottis.
The smooth muscle tissue present in the tunica media which is the middle layer of the wall of the arterial system.
The outermost, toughest, and most fibrous of the membranes (meninges) that surround and protect the brain.
The areas of the brain composed of neurons and (in contrast to the white matter) unmyelinated nerve fibers.
Any of the steps that convert a fresh tissue to a specimen ready for microscopy.
A method for rapid diagnosis that uses a frozen tissue sample rather than a chemically fixed sample.

A neoplasm that arises from the female reproductive system and is characterized by the absence of atypical or malignant cytological and architectural features, and absence of invasive features or metastatic potential.
The correlation coefficients between variable and factors.
A reduced quantity of a therapeutic agent prescribed to be taken at one time or at stated intervals.
The regular strength or dosage quantity of a therapeutic agent prescribed to be taken at one time or at stated intervals.
A blood clot in a deep vein, predominantly in the lower extremity, but may include the pelvis or upper extremity.
A British Overseas Territory comprising a peninsula on the southern coast of Cyprus.
